# Get numerical columns
numerical_cols = credit.select_dtypes(include=['float64']).columns

features_to_normalize = ['Time'] + [f'V{i}' for i in range(1, 29)] + ['Amount']

# Creating a copy of the original DataFrame for handling outliers
data_cleaned = credit.copy()

# Whiskers Approach to detect and handle outliers
for col in features_to_normalize:
    # Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
    Q1 = data_cleaned[col].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = data_cleaned[col].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1  # Calculate IQR

    # Define lower and upper bounds
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

        # Replace outliers with the median
    
    data_cleaned[col] = np.where((data_cleaned[col] < lower_bound) | (data_cleaned[col] > upper_bound), 
                                  data_cleaned[col].median(), 
                                  data_cleaned[col])

# Display the cleaned DataFrame shape
print(f"Original Data Shape: {credit.shape}")
print(f"Cleaned Data Shape: {data_cleaned.shape}")

The Whiskers Approach (IQR Method) is typically the preferred option for the Credit Card Fraud Detection dataset because of the following characteristics for credit dataset:

  1. Robust to Skewed Distributions: It performs well with the skewed distribution commonly seen in this binary classification scenario, where fraudulent activities are infrequent.

  2. Handling Imbalance: By closely considering the IQR, it balances out the representation of both legitimate and fraudulent transactions, making it less likely that fraudulent transactions are misclassified as outliers.

  3. Data Integrity: It avoids the excessive influence of outliers on mean and standard deviation calculations, which is critical in a dataset where misclassifying legitimate extreme transactions could skew analyses and models.

  1. (6 Points) Evaluate the performance of the logistic regression model using Log-Loss (Cross-Entropy).

    a. Calculate the log-loss for the logistic regression model on the test set. Do this calculation manually using numpy only (no explicit library functions).

    b. Compare the log-loss value with the other evaluation metrics (accuracy, precision, recall, F1-Score).

    c. Comment on what log-loss reveals about the model’s performance in comparison to other metrics and how it handles misclassified probabilities.

In [ ]:
# Get predicted probabilities for class 1
y_probs = models['Logistic Regression'].predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

# True labels for test set
y_true = y_test.values

# Calculate Log-Loss manually
N = len(y_true)
log_loss = -np.sum(y_true * np.log(y_probs) + (1 - y_true) * np.log(1 - y_probs)) / N

print(f"Log-Loss: {log_loss:.4f}")

Log-Loss: 0.0095

Log-loss is influenced by the level of certainty in predictions. A small log-loss value (0.0095) indicates that the model is able to predict fraud instances with a high level of confidence, leading to minimal consequences for incorrect classifications. It indicates that the model's probabilities are accurate for identifying fraud, but there is a high rate of misclassification due to low recall.

  • Comparison with other measurements:

    • Despite a low log-loss, the ability to detect fraudulent cases may still be lacking, as indicated by the recall and F1 score. Therefore, it is important to not depend only on log-loss, particularly in situations with imbalances, where the expenses of false negatives can be substantial.

  • Dealing with incorrectly classified probabilities:

    • Log-loss penalizes wrong predictions by considering the certainty of the prediction instead of just focusing on the number of correct classifications. If the model predicts numerous transactions as non-fraud when they are actually fraud, the log-loss will rise significantly, prompting enhancements in both accuracy and recall, not just precision.

plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='red', linestyle='--')  # Diagonal line
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve')
plt.legend(loc='lower right')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Print AUC value
print(f"AUC: {roc_auc:.4f}")

AUC: 0.8346

The model demonstrated outstanding discriminative ability with an AUC (Area Under the Curve) of 0.8346. A high AUC value indicates that the model is highly capable of differentiating between fraudulent and non-fraudulent transactions.

  • The True Positive Rate (TPR) is the percentage of real positives that the model correctly identifies, displayed on the y-axis.

  • The False Positive Rate (FPR) on the x-axis shows the percentage of real negatives that are mistakenly classified as positives.

Insights from ROC:

  • The steep initial rise of the curve is advantageous because it indicates that the model can achieve a high true positive rate while keeping the false positive rate relatively low.
  • The curve plateaus, showing that performance starts decreasing as the false positive rate goes up.

Insights from AUC:

  • An AUC value of 0.83 indicates a high degree of differentiation between the fraudulent and non-fraudulent classes. It suggests that the model can accurately order the likelihood of fraud compared to non-fraud transactions in a large majority of cases.

The diagonal red line in the plot represents the performance of a random classifier, which has an AUC of 0.5. The logistic regression model's AUC of 0.83 is well above this, indicating that it provides a strong classification capability.

Overall Performance:

  • Although the model has high accuracy and precision, it has a low recall of 8.16%, indicating it has difficulty detecting real fraud instances. This difference indicates that although the model accurately predicts a small number of real fraud cases, it misses a large number of them. The ROC curve and AUC can provide a more detailed perspective compared to solely focusing on accuracy or precision.

  • The ROC curve's behavior indicates that improving recall will likely increase false positives. This is particularly important in fraud detection; while high precision is valuable, being able to capture as many fraudulent transactions as possible (high recall) is critical.
